'''Mark Jenkins''' (born 1970) is an [[United States|American]] [[artist]] who makes sculptural [[street installations]]. Jenkins' practice of [[street art]] is to use the "street as a stage" where his sculptures interact with the surrounding environment including passersby who unknowingly become actors.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mutualart/the-surreal-art-of-an-urb_b_1426369.html The Surreal Art of an Urban Prankster <!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Huffington Post'', April 16, 2012</ref> His installations often draw the attention of the police.<ref>[http://www.journalnow.com/relishnow/article_f48dbcd9-d2d3-59fe-941d-eb69bd126ca1.html Testing the Limits: Artist's project misunderstood right off the bat, but it drew attention to art] ''Winston-Salem Journal'', October 11, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.journalnow.com/relishnow/article_0b904f0a-8802-5995-b894-357d3e0c432e.html Police remove another piece of artist's work <!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Winston-Salem Journal'', October 15, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.journalnow.com/relishnow/article_daaec832-3ada-568c-9654-0b23ae9d726d.html Artist's mannequin awaits permission to startle people  <!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Winston-Salem Journal'', November 3, 2009</ref>  His work has been described as whimsical, macabre, shocking and situationist.<ref>[http://mb.mercedes-benz.com/en/article/1044/Urban+Theatre Urban Theater] mb!, April 17, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2095360/Dont-911-The-disconcerting-sculptures-causing-panic-streets.html Don't call 911! The terrifying life-like sculptures bringing panic to the streets] The Daily Mail, Feb 2, 2012</ref> Jenkins cites [[Juan Muñoz]] as his initial inspiration.<ref>[http://www.themorningnews.org/gallery/let-no-man-scare-you Let No Man Scare You<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Morning News'', March 30, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mutualart/the-surreal-art-of-an-urb_b_1426369.html The Surreal Art of an Urban Prankster <!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Huffington Post'', April 16, 2012</ref>

In addition to creating art, he also teaches his sculpture techniques and installation practices through workshops. He currently lives in [[Washington, DC]].

== Life and Career ==

<div style="float: right; clear: right; margin-left: 1.4em;">
[[Image:Storker metro.jpg|thumb|none|195px|''Storker Project'']]
</div>

Jenkins was born in [[Alexandria, Virginia]], but first began experimenting with tape as a casting medium for creating sculpture in 2003 while living in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. Wrapping the tape in reverse and then resealing it, he was able to make casts of objects including himself. One of his first street projects was a series of clear tape self casts that he installed on the streets of Rio de Janeiro.  Jenkins became immediately interested in the reactions of the people and considered his installation as much a social experiment as an art project.<ref>[http://www.themorningnews.org/gallery/let-no-man-scare-you Let No Man Scare You<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Morning News'', March 30, 2006</ref>''

<div style="float: left; clear: left; margin-right: 1.4em;">
[[Image:Tape giraffe.jpg|thumb|none|185px|''Tape Giraffe'']]
</div>

In 2004 he moved back to Washington DC and in 2005 he began working with Sandra Fernandez on the ''Storker Project'', a series in which clear casts of toy babies are installed in different cities to interact with their surrounding environment.<ref>[http://www.themorningnews.org/gallery/let-no-man-scare-you Let No Man Scare You<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Morning News'', March 30, 2006</ref>  Jenkins and Fernandez continued to create other installations using tape animals--dogs playing in litter, giraffes nibbling plastic bags from trees, and ducks swimming in gutters. Other outdoor projects which explore [[culture jamming]] include ''Meterpops'', ''Traffic-Go-Round'', and ''Signs of Spring''.<ref>[http://boingboing.net/2007/03/14/mark-jenkinss-traffi.html Mark Jenkins's Traffic-Go-Round] ''BoingBoing'', March 14, 2006</ref><ref>[http://laughingsquid.com/signs-of-spring-by-mark-jenkins/ Signs of Spring] Laughing Squid, March 31, 2008</ref>

In 2006 Jenkins began the ''Embed Series.'' The tape casts were filled with newspaper and cement and dressed to create hyper realistic sculptural duplicates of himself and Fernandez. These new lifelike sculpture installations created confusion causing some passers-by to make calls to 911 which caused police and sometimes rescue units to arrive on his "stage".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/21/AR2006072100286.html That's Mark Jenkins All Over] ''The Washington Post'', July 23, 2006</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/01/us-germany-art-markjenkins-idUSTRE8101KI20120201 A Minute With: Street artist Mark Jenkins] ''Reuters'', February 1, 2012</ref>
<div style="float: right; clear: right; margin-left: 1.4em;">
[[Image:Flowersign.jpg|thumb|none|185px|''Signs of Spring'']]
</div>
In 2008 Jenkins collaborated with [[Greenpeace]] on an awareness campaign, ''Plight of the Polar Bears'', to draw attention to the [[Climate change in the Arctic|melting Arctic ice caps]]. Jenkins created realistic figures appearing to be homeless people but with plush polar bear heads. The installations resulted in bomb squads being deployed to destroy the works subsequently creating controversy over the regulation of public space in the post 9/11 era.<ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/usa/en/news-and-blogs/news/homelessness-among-polar-bears/ As Arctic Sea Ice reaches 2008 low, Street Art project highlights shared fate of polar bears, humanity<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Greenpeace USA'', September 18, 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/daniel-kessler/homeless-polar-bears-ask_b_127201.html Homeless Polar Bears Ask for Change<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Huffington Post'', September 17, 2008</ref><ref>[http://boingboing.net/2008/09/30/mark-jenkins-homeles.html Mark Jenkins homeless polar bear prank] ''BoingBoing'', September 30, 2008</ref>

Jenkins has participated in public art events ''Interferencia'' (Barcelona, 2008), ''BELEF'' (Belgrade, 2009), ''[[Dublin Contemporary 2011]]'',  ''Inside Out'' ([[Southeastern Center for Contemporary Art]], Winston-Salem, 2009),''Living Layers'' (Rome, 2012) and ''Les Vraisemblables'' (''[[Nuit Blanche]]'', Paris, 2014).

Indoors Jenkins has exhibited internationally in galleries and museums as well as continuing his ''Embed Series'' in public settings such as cafeterias, schools and building lobbies. Solo shows  include ''Glazed Paradise'' at Diesel Gallery (Tokyo, 2008),<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2008/06/19/arts/mark-jenkins-and-miho-kinomura-glazed-paradise/#.UWsbR4LbUSE Mark Jenkins and Miho Kinomura: Glazed Paradise] ''The Japan Times'', June 19, 2008</ref> ''Meaning is Overrated'' at Carmichael Gallery (Los Angeles, 2009), ''Terrible Horrible'' at Ruttkowski;68 Gallery (Cologne, 2014), ''Moment of Impact'' at Lazarides Gallery (London, 2015)<ref>{{cite web | title = Lazinc – Mark Jenkins - Moment of Impact | url = https://www.lazinc.com/exhibitions/46/ | accessdate = 19 July 2017  }}</ref>, and ''Remix'' at L'Arsenal (Montreal, 2016).

In 2018, he and Fernandez created ''[[Project84]]'', in London, England.<ref name="Barr">{{cite web|title=Harrowing sculptures appear on top of ITV buildings to raise awareness around male suicide |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/itv-male-suicide-awareness-sculptures-building-roof-mental-health-project-84-calm-a8274326.html |first1=Sabrina |last1=Barr |website=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=27 March 2018 |date=26 March 2018}}</ref><ref name="Marris">{{cite web |title=Project 84: Charity CALM calls for action on male suicide |url=https://news.sky.com/story/project-84-charity-calm-calls-for-action-on-male-suicide-11305108 |first1=Sharon |last1=Marris |publisher=[[Sky News]] |accessdate=27 March 2018 |date=27 March 2018}}</ref><ref name="ES">{{cite web |title=Eighty four harrowing suicide statues appear on roof of ITV studio |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/eighty-four-statues-of-male-suicide-victims-appear-on-itvs-southbank-studios-in-striking-campaign-a3799271.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=27 March 2018 |date=26 March 2018}}</ref> The work was designed to raise awareness of adult male suicide.<ref name="Barr" /> 

Commercially, Jenkins collaborated with the fashion brand [[Balenciaga]]<ref>{{cite web | title = The First Demna-Designed US Balenciaga Store is as Off the Wall as Expected | url =https://www.harpersbazaar.com/fashion/designers/a9985067/balenciaga-madison-avenue-store/ | accessdate = 6 June 2017  }}</ref> at stores including [[Colette (boutique)]] and [[Selfridges]].

