'''Sell-through''' refers to the [[percentage]] of a product that is sold by  a retailer after being shipped by its supplier, typically expressed as a percentage.<ref name="Blattner2004">{{cite book|author=Patrick Blattner|title=Using Microsoft Office Excel 2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4nJoWGI1P8wC&pg=PA676|year=2004|publisher=Que Publishing|isbn=978-0-7897-2953-8|pages=676–}}</ref><ref name="Milady2012">{{cite book|author=Milady|title=Retail Management for Salons and Spas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YqFuCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=18 December 2012|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-285-60845-7|pages=93–}}</ref> [[Net sales]] essentially refers to the same thing, in absolute numbers. Sell-through is calculated during a period (usually 1 month).<ref name="Chiplunkar2011">{{cite book|author=Chiplunkar|title=Product Category Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J2Um7Z-VghQC&pg=PA76|year=2011|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-0-07-015320-2|pages=76–}}</ref>

Sell through refers to sales made directly (Direct sales). [[Sell in]], on the other hand, refers to sales made through a channel.

This is relevant to sweet retail management software programs.

See also [[electronic sell-through]]

