[[File:Nshima_and_Beef_Relish_from_Proteas_Hotel,_Chingola,_Zambia.jpg|thumb|[[Nshima]] and beef relish from Proteas Hotel, Chingola, Zambia.|alt=Nshima and beef relish from Proteas Hotel, Chingola, Zambia.|300x300px]]
'''Zambian cuisine''' is heavily centered around [[nshima]], which is a food prepared from pounded white [[maize]]. Nshima is part of nearly every [[Zambia|Zambian]] meal. In addition to nshima, Zambian cuisine includes various types of [[stew]], cooked [[Vegetable|vegetables]] and different types of [[beer]]. Dried fish and insects are also eaten. 

== About ==

=== Food ===
Zambia's [[staple food]] is [[maize]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=funk&AN=ZA001200&site=ehost-live|title=Funk & Wagnalls New World Encyclopedia|last=|first=|publisher=World Book Inc.|year=2017|isbn=|location=Chicago|pages=|subscription=yes|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref> [[Nshima]] makes up the main component of Zambian meals and is made from pounded white maize.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mushemifire.com/baked-under-the-zambian-sun-interview-with-mushemi-fire/|title=Baked Under The Zambian Sun - Interview with Mushemi Fire - Mushemi Fire|last=|first=|date=|website=Meshemi Fire|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503030620/https://www.mushemifire.com/baked-under-the-zambian-sun-interview-with-mushemi-fire/|archive-date=3 May 2016|access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref>{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=50}} It is served with "relish," stew and vegetables and eaten by hand (preferably the right hand).<ref name=":0" />{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=50}} Nshima is eaten during lunch and dinner.<ref name=":1" /> Nshima may be made at home, at food stalls and at restaurants.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=50}}{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=93}} In traditional communities, the making of nshima is a long process, which includes drying the maize, sorting the kernels, pounding it and then finally cooking it.<ref name=":02">{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesoftheworld.org/hosted/chewa/|title=The Chewa|last=Gough|first=Amy|date=2004|website=|publisher=The Peoples of The World Foundation|accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> 

The types of relish eaten with nshima can be very simple, such as ''chibwabwa'', or [[pumpkin]] leaves.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=93}} Or it may be much fancier, and therefore, more expensive.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=93}} Other names for the relish are ''ndiwo, ndiyo'', ''umunani'' or ''dende''.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hungerforculture.com/?page_id=591|title=Nshima and Ndiwo: Zambian Staple Food|last=Tembo|first=Mwizenge S.|date=|website=Hunger For Culture|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224091611/http://www.hungerforculture.com/?page_id=591|archive-date=24 February 2017|access-date=2018-02-18}}</ref> The relish made with green vegetables is generally known as ''delele'' or ''thelele''.<ref name=":1" /> A unique way to create relish relies on cooking with ''chidulo'' and ''kutendela''.<ref name=":1" /> ''Chidulo'' is used in dishes made with green, leafy vegetables and also for wild mushrooms.<ref name=":1" /> The ''chidulo'' is made of burnt, dry [[banana]] leaves, bean stalks or maize stalks and leaves.<ref name=":1" /> The ashes are then collected, added to water and strained.<ref name=":1" /> The resulting liquid tastes like [[vinegar]].<ref name=":1" /> ''Kutendela'' is a prepared [[peanut]] powder made of pounded raw peanuts and is added to the chidulo sauce.<ref name=":1" />

''Ifisashi'' is another common food in Zambia.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.congocookbook.com/vegetable_and_side_dish_recipes/ifisashi.html|title=Ifisashi|last=|first=|date=|website=The Congo Cookbook|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806082635/http://www.congocookbook.com:80/vegetable_and_side_dish_recipes/ifisashi.html|archive-date=6 August 2017|access-date=2018-02-18}}</ref> It is a type of stew, made with greens and peanuts and served with nshima.<ref name=":2" /> ''Ifisashi'' can be [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] or cooked meat can be added to the stew.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgWrCQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA66&dq=Ifisashi&pg=PA66#v=onepage&q=Ifisashi&f=false|title=The Multicultural Cookbook for Students, 2nd Edition|last=Webb|first=Lois Sinaiko|last2=Roten|first2=Lindsay Grace|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2009|isbn=9780313375590|location=Santa Barbara, California|pages=66|language=en}}</ref> [[Samp]] is also eaten in Zambia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zambia-advisor.com/zambian-maize.html|title=Zambian Maize Staple Food|last=|first=|date=|work=Zambia Advisor|access-date=2018-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403220455/https://www.zambia-advisor.com/zambian-maize.html|archive-date=3 April 2017|dead-url=}}</ref>

[[Kapenta]], a small [[sardine]] from [[Lake Tanganyika]] has been introduced in lakes in Zambia.{{Sfn|Nyakupfuka|2013|p=69}} The fish is caught and dried to be cooked later, or it can be cooked fresh.{{Sfn|Nyakupfuka|2013|p=69}} [[Gizzard|Gizzards]] are also a popular delicacy in Zambia.{{Sfn|Nyakupfuka|2013|p=120}}

Various insects are also eaten. These include stink bugs,{{Sfn|Nyakupfuka|2013|p=73}} and [[Gonimbrasia belina|mopani worms]].{{Sfn|Nyakupfuka|2013|p=33}}

=== Alcohol ===
In Zambia, traditional [[beer]] is made from maize.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=94}} Individual villages once brewed their own recipes and it was shared communally.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=94-95}} Maize beer is also brewed commercially in [[Lusaka]], with Chibuku and Shake-Shake being popular brands.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=95}} Other types of beer that are popular include Mosi and Rhino.{{Sfn|Else|2002|p=94}} The first Zambian beer festival was held on September 25, 2009 at the [[Barclays Sports Complex]] in Lusaka.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zambia-advisor.com/Zambia-Beer-Festival.html|title=The First Zambia Beer Festival|last=|first=|date=|work=Zambia Advisor|access-date=2018-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607034813/http://www.zambia-advisor.com:80/Zambia-Beer-Festival.html|archive-date=7 June 2017|dead-url=}}</ref>

== History ==
The use of [[maize]] in dishes such as ''nsima'' or ''nshima'' happened during the latter half of the twentieth century.{{Sfn|McCann|2009|p=139}}

The [[Bemba people]], who live in what is now Zambia, traditionally ate what was available depending on weather patterns.{{Sfn|McCann|2009|p=18}} Bemba meals included a type of thick [[porridge]] made of [[millet]] called ''ubwali'' which was eaten with "relish" called ''umunani''.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=46}} ''Ubwali'' was eaten with nearly every meal.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=47}} ''Umunani'' was most often a type of stew made with meat, fish, insects or vegetables.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=48-49}} The Bemba preferred to eat ''ubwali'' with only one type of relish at a time.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=49}} The stews made with meat and vegetables were cooked with salt and sometimes [[Groundnut|ground-nuts]].{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=49}} Generally, the Bemba did not eat raw food.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=53}} Overall, Bemba cooking was fairly plain in taste and only occasionally acidic or spicy.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=54-55}} Beer was an imprortant part of social events for the Bemba people and beer was brewed often during harvest months.{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=78}}{{Sfn|Richards|1939|p=79-80}} 

Like the Bemba, the [[Chewa people]] also eat a [[porridge]], called ''nsima'', which is eaten with vegetables and used as a scoop.<ref name=":02" />

The [[Tonga people (Zambia and Zimbabwe)|Tonga people]] of the region have traditionally eaten insects which are cooked or dried.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepatriot.co.zw/old_posts/nutritious-insects-among-the-batonga/|title=Nutritious insects among the BaTonga|last=Siamonga|first=Elliot|date=24 August 2017|website=Celebrating Being Zimbabwean|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210053/https://www.thepatriot.co.zw/old_posts/nutritious-insects-among-the-batonga/|archive-date=18 February 2018|access-date=2018-02-18}}</ref>

